### Ablation studies

To verify the design choices in our method, we conduct ablation studies on SHHQ dataset, which contains diverse appearances, _i.e._, various human body, face, and hand poses as well as clothes.

**Representation.** XAGen adopts a multi-scale and multi-part representation to improve the quality for face and hands regions. We study the necessity of this design by removing Tri-planes for face and hands. Table 3(a) provides the results, indicating that using only a single full-body Tri-plane (without any specific Tri-planes for face or hands) results in a significant degradation in appearance quality. Adding either face or hand Tri-plane can alleviate this issue and all the FID metrics drop slightly. The best results are achieved when both face and hand Tri-planes are enabled, demonstrating the importance of our multi-scale and multi-part representation.

**Multi-part rendering.** In our model, we render multiple parts independently in the forward process to disentangle the learning of body, face, and hands. Table 3(b) demonstrates that independent rendering for face is crucial, as it significantly improves both fidelity (FID\({}_{}\): 20.63 _vs._ 10.06) and control ability (Exp: 6.58 _vs._ 5.56, Jaw: 7.26 _vs._ 6.57) for face. Similarly, without rendering for hand, FID\({}_{}\) increases from 18.85 to 25.94, and MSE increases from 3.28 to 4.55 (Table 3(c)). The effectiveness of multi-part rendering is further supported by the qualitative results shown in Figure 5. Without independent rendering, the geometry quality degrades. For example, the eyes and mouth are collapsed without face rendering, and the model also fails to synthesize geometric details for hand when hand rendering is disabled. These highlight the importance of multi-part rendering in facilitating the learning of 3D geometries for different body parts.

